===1&nbsp;800 million years ago to 550 million years ago=== {| class="wikitable" |- ! style="background:silver;" abbr="Interval"|'''Time interval, before the present time. a=[[annus]] (year)''' ! style="background:silver;" abbr="Period"|'''[[List of time periods|Period]]''' ! style="background:silver;" abbr="Event"| '''Event, [[invention]] or historical development''' |- | align=center |1.8 Ga – 1.4 Ga||End of Paleoproterozoic, beginning of [[Mesoproterozoic]] era|| Fossils of [[red algae]].<!--1.6 Ga--><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Mattias Karlsson|title=Oldest plant-like fossils found in rock|journal=New Scientist|date=Mar 18, 2017|url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/mg23331172-900-oldest-plantlike-fossils-discovered-are-16-billion-years-old}}</ref> Erosion of [[granite]] introduces [[copper]], [[zinc]], and [[molybdenum]] into surface waters.<ref>[https://www.newscientist.com/article/dn21947 "Sex born from hard rock and heavy metal"] by Will Ferguson, ''New Scientist'', 23 June 2012, pp. 10–11.</ref> |- | align=center |1.4 Ga – 1.1 Ga||Mesoproterozoic era|| Eukaryotes found in lakes.<ref>[https://www.newscientist.com/article/dn20373-ancient-lakes-show-when-eukaryotic-life-left-the-sea.html "Ancient lakes show when eukaryotic life left the sea"] by Colin Barras, ''New Scientist'', April 16, 2011, p. 20. {{cite journal | doi = 10.1038/nature09943 | volume=473 | issue=7348 | title=Earth's earliest non-marine eukaryotes | year=2011 | journal=Nature | pages=505–509 | last1 = Strother | first1 = Paul K. | last2 = Battison | first2 = Leila | last3 = Brasier | first3 = Martin D. | last4 = Wellman | first4 = Charles H.| bibcode=2011Natur.473..505S }}</ref> |- | align=center| 1.1 Ga – 900 [[Ma (unit)|Ma]] ||End of Mesoproterozoic, beginning of [[Neoproterozoic]] era. [[Tonian]] period|| Coming together of [[Rodinia]] supercontinent. Appearance of [[sex]] (possibly). Traces of sponge-like animals.<ref>"[https://www.newscientist.com/article/dn17105-earliest-animal-traces-solve-timegap-mystery.html Earliest animal traces solve timegap mystery]", ''New Scientist'', 11 May 2009, p. 12.</ref><ref>[https://www.newscientist.com/article/mg20327161.200-dawn-of-the-animals-solving-darwins-dilemma.html?full=true "Dawn of the animals: Solving Darwin's dilemma"] by Douglas Fox and Michael Le Page, ''New Scientist'', 8 July 2009, pp. 38–41</ref> |- | align=center| 900 Ma – 700 Ma ||Cryogenian period || Breakup of [[Rodinia]], [[Sturtian glaciation]] begins,<!--717 Ma--> possible [[Snowball Earth]], [[volcanism]] on [[Venus]] practically stops |- | align=center| 700 Ma – 550 Ma ||End of Cryogenian, beginning of [[Ediacaran]] period|| [[Pannotia]] supercontinent forms,<!--ca 600 Ma--> then breaks up into [[Laurentia]], [[Gondwana]], [[Angaraland]] and [[Baltica]]. [[Marinoan glaciation]].<!--650-635 Ma--> First non-microscopic life ([[Ediacaran biota]]). [[Rangeomorph]]s. First fossils of [[animal]]s. |}
===550 million years ago to 180 million years ago=== {| class="wikitable" |- ! style="background:silver;" abbr="Interval"|'''Time interval, before the present time. a=[[annus]] (year)''' ! style="background:silver;" abbr="Period"|'''[[List of time periods|Period]]''' ! style="background:silver;" abbr="Event"| '''Event, [[invention]] or historical development''' |- | align=center| 550 Ma – 450 Ma || End of Ediacaran. [[Cambrian]] period (541–485 Ma) – [[Ordovician]] (485–443 Ma) || [[Cambrian explosion]]. [[Fish]]-like [[Myllokunmingia]], [[Haikouichthys]], & [[Pikaia]]. First [[conodonts]]. All modern mineralized phyla present.<ref name=Landing2010>{{Cite journal| doi = 10.1130/G30870.1| title = Cambrian origin of all skeletalized metazoan phyla--Discovery of Earth's oldest bryozoans (Upper Cambrian, southern Mexico)| year = 2010| last1 = Landing | first1 = E.| last2 = English | first2 = A.| last3 = Keppie | first3 = J. D.| journal = Geology| volume = 38| issue = 6| pages = 547–550|bibcode = 2010Geo....38..547L }}</ref> [[Bivalve]]s.<!--520 Ma for Fordilla--> [[Arthropod]]s dominant until arrival of [[Nautilus|chambered nautili]].<!--500 Ma--><ref>[https://www.newscientist.com/article/mg19826501.700-nautilus-chambers-of-secrets.html?full=true "Nautilus: Chambers of secret life"] by [[Peter Ward (paleontologist)|Peter Ward]], ''New Scientist'', 5 April 2008.</ref> Stifling hot "Dead Interval".<!--Last 50 Ma of Cambrian--><ref>{{cite journal|author1=Catherine Brahic|title=Volcanic mayhem drove major burst of evolution|journal=New Scientist|url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/mg22129522.600-volcanic-mayhem-drove-major-burst-of-evolution.html|date=Jan 18, 2014|pages=6–7}}</ref> [[End-Botomian mass extinction]].<!--517 Ma--> [[Appalachian Mountains]] form.<!--480 Ma--> First fossils of [[plants]] and [[fungi]] on land<!-- 480-460Ma ago, or 500 acc. to Ward-->.<ref name=breath/> [[Great Ordovician Biodiversification Event]].<!--Beginning of Ordovician--> First [[eury