[[amphibian]]s,<!--370 Ma--> [[archaeopteris]] ([[tree fern]]s),<!--383-323 Ma--> [[seed]]s<!--Upper Devonian-->, [[coelacanth]]s<!--360 Ma-->. [[Late Devonian extinction]]s, culminating in the [[Hangenberg event]] and atmospheric [[oxygen]] falling to 13%. Few arthropods left on land.<ref name=breath/><!--Around 360 Ma--> Beginning of [[Karoo Ice Age]].<!--360-260 Ma--> [[Romer's gap]] in the tetrapod record.<!--360-345 Ma--> |- | align=center| 350 Ma – 280 Ma || [[Carboniferous]] (359–299 Ma), beginning of [[Permian]] (299–252 Ma) || [[Karoo Ice Age]]. Formation of [[Pangaea]] supercontinent. Oxygen levels rise and animals colonize the land a second time.<ref name=breath/> First winged [[insect]]s and [[reptiliomorph]]s such as [[Solenodonsaurus]]<!--320-305 Ma-->, [[synapsid]]s (forerunners of [[mammals]])<!--Archaeothyris at 320 Ma-->, and [[reptile]]s<!--Hylonomus at 315 Ma-->. Oxygen in atmosphere peaks, around 30%.<ref name=breath>{{cite journal|author1=Peter Ward|authorlink1=Peter Ward (paleontologist)|title=Oxygen – the breath of life|journal=New Scientist|date=April 28, 2007|pages=38–41|url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/mg19426012.000-oxygen--the-breath-of-life.html?full=true}} See also [https://www.newscientist.com/data/images/archive/2601/26012001.jpg accompanying graph].</ref> [[Carboniferous Rainforest Collapse]].<!--305 Ma ago--> |- | align=center| 280 Ma – 220 Ma ||Permian, [[Triassic]] (252–201 Ma)|| [[Cycad]]s,<!--from 280 Ma--> [[seed fern]]s. [[Therapsid]]s (forerunners of mammals) such as [[pelycosaur]]s and [[cynodont]]s. [[End-Capitanian extinction event]].<!--260 Ma--><ref>{{cite journal|author1=Jeff Hecht|title='Missing' disaster led to all-time worst extinction|journal=New Scientist|date=Oct 25, 2014|pages=6–7|url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/mg22429922.300-missing-disaster-led-to-alltime-worst-extinction.html#.VJ8Zg0NAQ}}</ref> [[Siberian Traps]] eruption and [[Permian-Triassic extinction event]]. [[Dinosaur tracks]].<ref>[https://www.newscientist.com/article/mg20827813.900.html "Meet the oldest dino ancestor yet"], ''New Scientist'', 6 Oct. 2010.</ref><ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1098/rspb.2010.1746 | volume=278 | issue=1708 | title=Footprints pull origin and diversification of dinosaur stem lineage deep into Early Triassic | year=2010 | journal=Proceedings of the Royal Society B: Biological Sciences | pages=1107–1113 | last1 = Brusatte | first1 = S. L.| pmc=3049033 }}</ref> 40&nbsp;°C sea temperatures during [[Early Triassic#Smithian-Spathian extinction|Smithian-Spathian extinction]]. [[Turtle]]s. Dominance of [[archosaur]]s: crocodile-like [[Crurotarsi]]. First [[pterosaur]]s, [[ichthyosaur]]s. [[Dinosaur]]s. [[Gymnosperm]]s dominant. [[Dicroidium]] flora common on land. [[Manicouagan Crater]] formed.<!--215 Mya--> First [[lizard]]s. |- | align=center| 220 Ma – 180 Ma || Triassic, [[Jurassic]] (201–145 Ma) || [[Central Atlantic magmatic province|Central Atlantic eruption]] and [[Triassic–Jurassic extinction event]].<!--201.3 Mya--> Oxygen in atmosphere hits low of about 12%.<ref name=breath/><!--End of Triassic--> Breakup of Pangaea into [[Gondwana]] and [[Laurasia]]. [[Mammal]]s. [[Gymnosperm]]s (especially [[conifer]]s, [[Bennettitales]], and [[cycad]]s) and [[fern]]s common. [[Sauropod]]s, [[carnosaur]]s, [[stegosaur]]s. [[Toarcian turnover]] (extinction).<!--183 Ma ago--> [[Gondwana]] breaks up. |}
