{{more citations needed|date=October 2015}}

{{Wiktionary|Sigillography}}[[Image:sealtaglarge.jpg|thumb|right|Pine [[resin]] seal on [[vellum]] tag or tail of an  English [[deed]] ''(1638)''.]]

'''Sigillography''' (sometimes referred to under its Greek name, '''sphragistics''') is one of the [[auxiliary sciences of history]]. It refers to the study of [[Seal (emblem)|seals]] attached to [[document]]s as a source of historical information. It concentrates on the legal and social meaning of seals, as well as the evolution of their design. It has links to [[diplomatics]], [[heraldry]], [[social history]], and the [[Art history|history of art]].

[[Antiquarian|Antiquaries]] began to record historic seals in the 15th century, and in the 16th and 17th centuries their study became a fairly widespread antiquarian activity.<ref>{{cite book |first1=P.D.A. |last1=Harvey |first2=Andrew |last2=McGuinness |title=A Guide to British Medieval Seals |location=London |publisher=British Library and Public Record Office |year=1996 |pages=22–6 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite book| first=Elizabeth |last=New |title=Seals and Sealing Practices |publisher=British Records Association |series=Archives and the User |volume=11 |year=2010 |location=London |ISBN=978-0-900222-15-3 |pages=29–32}}</ref> The term sigillography is first found in the works of [[Jean Mabillon]] in the late 17th century, and in those of [[Johann Michael Heineccius]] soon afterwards.{{Citation needed|date=February 2007}} Initially thought of as a branch of [[diplomatics]], the discipline gradually became an independent branch of historical studies.

In the second half of the 19th century sigillography was further developed by German and French historians, among them [[Hermann Grotefend]], [[Otto Posse]], [[Louis-Claude Douet d'Arcq]] and [[Germain Demay]].{{Citation needed|date=February 2007}}

Sigillography is also an important subdiscipline of [[Byzantine studies]], involving the study of Byzantine lead seal impressions and the text and images thereon. Its importance derives from both the scarcity of surviving Byzantine documents themselves, and from the large number (over 40,000) of extant seals.<ref>{{cite book | editor-first = Alexander| editor-last = Kazhdan | title = [[Oxford Dictionary of Byzantium]] | publisher = Oxford University Press | year = 1991 | isbn = 978-0-19-504652-6 | pages=1894–1895}}</ref> One of the largest compendiums of Byzantine seals can be found in the large-volume by Gustave Schlumberger, "Sigillographie de l'empire Byzantin", published in 1904.<ref>{{cite book | editor-first = Gustave| editor-last = Schlumberger | title = [[Sigillographie de l'empire Byzantin]] | publisher = Ernest Leroux | year = 1904 }}</ref>

==Popular culture ==

Sigillography features in the plot of "[[King Ottokar's Sceptre]]", one of ''[[The Adventures of Tintin]]''.

